          "body": "The chapter closes with Rehoboam's domestic arrangements — two named primary wives, eighteen total wives, sixty concubines, twenty-eight sons, and sixty daughters. The Chronicler records this without direct censure, but the catalogue is not neutral. Rehoboam's polygamy violates the royal law of Deuteronomy 17:17 ('he shall not multiply wives for himself'), and his chosen heir is Abijah, the son of Maacah — the daughter of Absalom, David's rebellious son who tore the kingdom apart through pride and violence (2 Samuel 15-18). The irony is layered: Rehoboam chooses as his queen-mother figure the granddaughter of the man who most nearly destroyed the Davidic throne. And he seeks 'many wives' for his sons — distributing both his sons and his marital patterns to the fortified cities. The practical wisdom of verse 23 (*bin*, to act discerningly) in distributing his sons is real — it prevents court coups by keeping potential rivals occupied in provincial administration. But the same verse notes he sought many wives for them. The wisdom is administrative; the pattern is dysfunctional. The chapter ends, therefore, on a note of deep ambiguity: the king who listened to a prophet, built defensive walls, and received the faithful migrants from all Israel is also the king who loved a woman above all others, multiplied wives contrary to the law, and chose succession by personal preference rather than divine guidance. All of this will surface in chapters 12-13 with full force."
