        "excerpt": "Rehoboam lived in Jerusalem and built cities for defense in Judah.",
        "body": "The building program of 11:5-12 is a set piece of royal stewardship that the Chronicler presents as evidence of the blessing that accompanies covenant obedience. Fifteen cities, each provisioned with food, oil, wine, shields, and spears — the logistics of a competently administered defense system. The arc of the fortified cities runs through the Shephelah (the foothills west of Judah), guarding the main invasion corridors from Philistia and Egypt. Lachish, the most strategically important site, sits at the junction of the major routes from the coast to Hebron. Azekah guards the Valley of Elah. Adullam sits in the hill country above the coastal plain.\n\nFor the Chronicler's post-exilic audience, this list carried enormous resonance. Lachish and Azekah were the last fortified cities to fall before Jerusalem was taken by Nebuchadnezzar (Jeremiah 34:7). They had been Rehoboam's defensive anchor 350 years earlier. The Chronicler is tracing the long arc of Judah's history through these very sites — and implying that fortification without covenant fidelity (as chapter 12 will demonstrate) is ultimately insufficient. Shishak sacked these same cities in Rehoboam's fifth year.\n\nThe Chronicler's silence on any moral critique of the building program is itself an interpretive signal. In Chronicles, what is presented without censure during a king's faithful period is credited to that fidelity. Compare the elaborate building programs of Solomon (2 Chron. 2-4) or Asa (14:6-7, explicitly linked to covenant fidelity) or Jehoshaphat (17:12-13). Rehoboam's construction belongs to the same category — prudent use of resources during the years he walked in the way of David.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Matsor* (fortification, defense, siege-work) — the same word used for Jerusalem under siege. Rehoboam builds *arei matsor*, cities-of-siege-defense, to prevent the kind of encirclement Jerusalem would eventually suffer. *Chazaq* (to strengthen, 11:11, 12) is the chapter's key verb of strengthening — used for both military fortification and the Levites' strengthening of the kingdom (11:17), binding the physical and spiritual dimensions of the kingdom's health."
